data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration is needed here.**

Your code only uses `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — none of which are affected by the .NET 6+ breaking change. These APIs work identically in modern .NET. The code will compile and run correctly as-is on .NET 8.

---

**Optional modernization** (unrelated to Thread.Abort migration):

If you'd like to modernize the code, you could replace manual thread management with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.Run`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, item => Process(item));
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This is purely optional and offers better thread-pool utilization — it is **not** required for .NET 8 compatibility.
